This paper deals with deep neural networks and their performance on data from unseen sources, which is a common problem in computer vision (CV) and machine learning (ML) research. The paper specifically focuses on the task of segmentation of white matter hyperintensities (WMH) in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scans, which falls under the sub-category of computer vision (cs.CV). The use of deep neural networks (DNNs) and semi-supervised domain adaptation methods also suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.NE). Finally, the use of MRI scans suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of multimedia (cs.MM).
